<div id="review_5280156" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/5280156" />
    <a title="Kiki" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/169109-kiki"><img alt="Kiki" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1277131921p2/169109.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/5280156?book_show_action=true">Aug 29, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kiki" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kiki" href="/user/show/169109-kiki">Kiki</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/169109-kiki?shelf=literature-fiction">literature-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer5280156" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15953130647580378334">Great summer read with all the pomp and circumstance you&apos;d expect for a novel about the royal court of 15th century Moghul Empire (which included what today is Pakistan, Iran, Afghanistan and most of India)<br/><br/>Mehrunnisa aka Empress Nur Jahan was one of the most powerful empresses of the Moghul Empire only her story is just now coming to light based on a pulling together of anecdotal mentions in books on the country and famous men at that time.<br/><br/>This is the first of two books on her life. This first, </span>
  <span id="freeText15953130647580378334" style="display:none">Great summer read with all the pomp and circumstance you'd expect for a novel about the royal court of 15th century Moghul Empire (which included what today is Pakistan, Iran, Afghanistan and most of India)<br /><br />Mehrunnisa aka Empress Nur Jahan was one of the most powerful empresses of the Moghul Empire only her story is just now coming to light based on a pulling together of anecdotal mentions in books on the country and famous men at that time.<br /><br />This is the first of two books on her life. This first, is a fun historical fiction novel about how she married Emperor Jahangir and became an Empress and why she knew how to read, do math and other things only highly educated men were allowed to learn at that time.<br /><br />Part two, which I didn't read yet, tells of what she did once she became empress. Her niece is Ajurmand aka Mumtaz Mahal, the woman Emporer Jahan built the Taj Mahal for. Ajurmand and Emeror Shah Jahan succeeded Mehrunnisa and the Emporer Jahangir.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15953130647580378334" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


