<div id="review_406374044" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/406374044" />
    <a title="Marcy prager" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1140398-marcy-prager"><img alt="Marcy prager" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1209997030p2/1140398.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/406374044?book_show_action=true">Sep 03, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marcy prager" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marcy prager" href="/user/show/1140398-marcy-prager">Marcy prager</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer406374044&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer406374044" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12340295719304907347">This is the beginning of the story of a Persian family who was immigrating to an unknown country due to the loss of position due to a ruler change in Persia. The mother of the family was about to give birth. The father had no money for milk or food for his family. With great unhappiness, the father took the baby and left her under a nearby tree, to hopefully be adopted. The baby came back to the father due to the generosity of a leader of a caravan, bound for India. He offered to present the fat</span>
  <span id="freeText12340295719304907347" style="display:none">This is the beginning of the story of a Persian family who was immigrating to an unknown country due to the loss of position due to a ruler change in Persia. The mother of the family was about to give birth. The father had no money for milk or food for his family. With great unhappiness, the father took the baby and left her under a nearby tree, to hopefully be adopted. The baby came back to the father due to the generosity of a leader of a caravan, bound for India. He offered to present the father to the court of Emperor Akbar in order to procure a “royal” job.<br /><br />This story is about Mehrunnissa, the baby who throughout her childhood, and the rest of her life, was in love with Emperor Akbar’s favorite son and prince, destined to become the next emperor. The Prince was in love with Mehrunnissa as well, but their union could not take place until she was thirty-four years old, due to the intrigue of the Mughal Empire. <br /><br />There were other empresses’ wishes to be considered, as well as the wishes of Emperor Akbar. There were also wars that took place to ensure the land of Hindustan that took the prince away in the name of Emperor Akbar. But most of all, there was the wish of the Prince to become Emperor before his time, which angered Akbar, banishing his son to distant places.<br /><br />In the meantime, Mehrunnissa was married to a soldier who was angered by Mehrunnisa’s infertility for many years, in addition to rebelling against Emperor Akbar to make another one of his sons the Emperor of India. Mehrunnissa suffered the loss of her family by being banished with her husband away from the royal court, in addition to being unloved by her husband, and “losing” the prince. <br /><br />I read the sequel before the first book, spoiling some of the events that took place in the first novel. The first book was fast to read, and very engaging. The intrigue of the Mughal Empire continues to fascinate me as I read novels such as this one! <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12340295719304907347" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


